  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's housing stock includes decades of owner-added structures: decks, garden sheds, carports, granny flats, covered patios, and room extensions. Some were properly approved and built to code. Others were not. A building certificate is a document that speaks specifically to the first category: it confirms that a structure that had an approval meets the requirements of that approval. It does not certify unapproved structures, and it does not give any general protection to a vendor who has undisclosed work on their property.</p>

      <p>Understanding what a building certificate actually covers, when you need one before selling, and how unapproved structures affect a sale is essential knowledge for any Brisbane seller with non-standard work on their property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a building certificate is in Queensland</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, a building certificate is issued under the Building Act 1975. It is issued by a private building certifier or, in some cases, by the local council. The certificate confirms that a particular structure, typically the primary dwelling, meets the requirements of its building approval and the applicable code at the time of construction. It is not a building inspection report, and it is not a general compliance clearance for the entire property.</p>

      <p>The key distinction is approval-specific. A building certificate can only be issued for a structure that had a formal approval. If a deck was added without development approval and building approval, no building certificate can be issued for it. The certifier will not inspect an unapproved structure and issue a certificate. The certificate applies to approved works only.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When sellers are required to obtain one</h2>
      <p>A building certificate is not a mandatory disclosure document in a standard Queensland residential sale. In most transactions, vendors are not legally required to obtain one before listing or before contract. However, there are circumstances where obtaining one is either required by the contract or strongly advisable as a practical matter.</p>

      <p>Some buyers, particularly those purchasing older homes with visible additions or alterations, will insert a special condition into the contract requiring the vendor to provide a building certificate for the primary structure. This is most common in sales involving properties with extensive renovation history or where the contract includes a due diligence period. If your contract includes such a condition, you will need to engage a private building certifier to inspect the structure and issue the certificate within the timeframe specified.</p>

      <p>Sellers of older Queenslanders and post-war homes in Brisbane's inner east sometimes choose to obtain a building certificate proactively before listing, particularly if they know the property has had significant renovation work and want to reduce the risk of contract delays or buyer concerns during due diligence. This is a judgment call, not a legal requirement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a building certificate does not cover</h2>
      <p>This is the most important point for sellers to understand. A building certificate does not certify unapproved structures. If a previous owner added a deck without approval, and a building certificate is issued for the main house, the deck is outside the scope of the certificate entirely. It remains an unapproved structure whether or not the rest of the property has been certified.</p>

      <p>A building certificate also does not address building defects unless those defects are serious enough to indicate non-compliance with the approval. It is not a structural engineering report. It does not certify that the plumbing, electrical, or waterproofing work was done to a standard that a building inspection might assess. Buyers who want that level of assurance will commission a building and pest inspection report, which is a completely separate document conducted by a separate professional.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between a building certificate and a pool safety certificate</h2>
      <p>Brisbane sellers with pools often encounter two separate certificate requirements. The pool safety certificate is a mandatory disclosure document: in Queensland, a seller must either provide a pool safety certificate (issued within the previous two years) or transfer the obligation to obtain one to the buyer by agreement, in which case the buyer has 90 days from settlement to obtain it. This is a distinct requirement from the building certificate, governed by the Building Act provisions relating to pool safety standards.</p>

      <p>A building certificate, as discussed above, relates to the structural compliance of buildings. A pool safety certificate relates to pool fence compliance and pool safety features. They cover different things, are issued by different professionals, and have different disclosure obligations attached. Sellers with pools should confirm their pool safety certificate status early in the pre-sale preparation process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How unapproved structures affect a sale</h2>
      <p>The practical impact of an unapproved structure on a sale depends on whether the buyer discovers it, and if so, how they respond. Buyers who commission a building and pest inspection will often have an inspector comment on structures that appear to lack approval, particularly if those structures show signs of age, are clearly recent additions, or differ visibly from council records. A buyer's solicitor will typically advise them of the implications when unapproved works are identified.</p>

      <p>The range of responses from buyers includes accepting the property as is, requesting a price reduction to account for the cost of regularising the works or demolishing the structure, or in more serious cases, making the issue the basis for a finance or due diligence clause. In a competitive market with multiple genuine buyers, an unapproved structure may not be a decisive factor. In a slower market, or if the unapproved work is substantial, it gives buyers leverage they will often use.</p>

      <p>The cost of regularising unapproved work varies. A simple deck with straightforward plans and a cooperative certifier might be resolved for a few thousand dollars. More substantial works, particularly if they require structural assessment or are non-compliant with current code, can cost significantly more and take several months. Sellers who are aware of unapproved structures should speak to a private building certifier and their solicitor about their options before going to market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cost and timeline for obtaining a building certificate</h2>
      <p>A building certificate for a residential property in Brisbane typically costs between $500 and $1,500 depending on the certifier and the complexity of the property. The timeline from engagement to certificate issuance is generally two to four weeks, assuming the inspection is straightforward and no compliance issues are identified. If the certifier identifies items requiring rectification, the timeline extends until those items are addressed.</p>

      <p>Building certifiers in Queensland must be licensed by the Queensland Building and Construction Commission. You can find a licensed certifier through the QBCC website or through your solicitor's referrals. Your real estate agent can also point you to certifiers who regularly work in your area and understand local council requirements.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When it makes sense to get one proactively</h2>
      <p>The strongest argument for obtaining a building certificate before listing is certainty. If you know the property has had significant renovation work, obtaining a certificate early means you are not discovering a compliance issue during the buyer's due diligence period when you have less time and less negotiating room to deal with it. It also allows you to disclose confidently and market the property with documentation that reduces uncertainty for buyers.</p>

      <p>The argument against is straightforward: if the property's history is clean and the renovation work was done under proper approvals, the certificate may not add meaningful value to the sale. Your agent and solicitor can help you assess whether the property's specific profile makes proactive certification worth the cost and time investment.</p>

